yeah, so i was thinking of a scenario like the following:

```
v0 = {
"a": int,
"b": float,
"c": string
}

v1 = {
"a": int,
"b": float,
"c": string,
"d": int
}

v2 = {
"a": int,
"b": float,
"d": int
}
```

in a chain like this where schema build off of each other. v1 would be an extension of v0, and v2 would be an extension of v1 (removing the key). We often have schema that build up on each other in chains like this, and sometimes in newer schema we depreciate keys. For small schema like this it may not seem all that useful. But for large schema, it is nice to be able to start from a base and remove and add keys easily.

