Personally, I prefer the original. Whilst it is certainly true that in the following example the `elif` could just be an `if` the `elif` provides more information at very little cost, you can immediately tell that only one of those code paths can be taken without having to read all the other if statements.

```python
def handle_api_error(self, rbody, rcode, resp):
        try:
            err = resp['error']
        except (KeyError, TypeError):
            raise error.APIError(
                "Invalid response object from API: %r (HTTP response code "
                "was %d)" % (rbody, rcode),
                rbody, rcode, resp)

        if rcode in [400, 404]:
            raise error.InvalidRequestError(
                err.get('message'), err.get('param'), rbody, rcode, resp)
        elif rcode == 401:
            raise error.AuthenticationError(
                err.get('message'), rbody, rcode, resp)
        elif rcode == 402:
            raise error.CardError(err.get('message'), err.get('param'),
                                  err.get('code'), rbody, rcode, resp)
        else:
            raise error.APIError(err.get('message'), rbody, rcode, resp)
```

In addition to this, whilst I would make no great effort to try and change code of the form:
```python
def example():
   #...
    if some_condition:
        return 1
    return 4
```
into the form:
```python
def example():
    #...
    if some_condition:
        return 1
    else:
        return 4
```
I believe the second is better for the same reason. "return 4" can only be executed if the if clause is false and syntax that expresses this lets a reader infer this without having to read the body of the if clause is, in my opinion, preferable.

