@xannz I assume the duplicate function name is a copy-paste error?  But the `@when_any('endpoint.{endpoint_name}.departed')` bit is also fundamentally incorrect, since that flag will be set when *any* unit is departing.  The correct logic would be:

```python
@when_any('endpoint.{endpoint_name}.joined')
def request_joined(self):
    set_flag(self.expand_name('available'))

@when_none('endpoint.{endpoint_name}.joined')
def request_broken(self):
    clear_flag(self.expand_name('available'))
    clear_flag(self.expand_name('departed'))
```

In that case, the flags should get cleaned up as expected during the `-broken` hook, which seems like the most reasonable timing.  (Well, it would be `-broken` except for the issue that it currently checks for relation IDs instead of units, which could cause a delay.  Even so, it would go to the expected state during the next hook to fire.)

That said, I'm not 100% committed to the behavior of waiting until the last unit is actually truly gone, but I'm still leaning that way since it seems more consistent with the charm's view of the world.

